{"_record_type": "fragment", "type": "expert_knowledge", "content": "# Q: Non-interactive commands fail to check system keychain for API key\n**Source:** https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli/issues/23567\n\n## The Problem / Request\n### What happened?\nWhen an API key is configured using the interactive `/auth` command, it is securely saved to the system keychain. However, subsequent non-interactive commands (e.g., `gemini extensions install`) fail with the following error:\n`When using Gemini API, you must specify the GEMINI_API_KEY environment variable. Update your environment and try again (no reload needed if using .env)!`\n\nThe CLI's startup validation (`validateNonInteractiveAuth`) is hardcoded to only check for the `GEMINI_API_KEY` environment variable and does not attempt to read from the keychain where the key was actually stored.\n\n### What did you expect to happen?\nNon-interactive commands should be able to authenticate using the API key stored in the system keychain, consistent with how the interactive mode operates. The CLI should check the keychain as a fallback if the `GEMINI_API_KEY` environment variable is missing.\n\n### Client information\nPlatform: macOS\nVersion: Development build (latest from `feature/ux-extension` branch)\n\n### Login information\nAPI Key configured via the interactive `/auth` command.\n\n### Anything else we need to know?\nThe root cause is in `packages/cli/src/config/auth.ts`. The `validateAuthMethod` function only checks `process.env['GEMINI_API_KEY']` and does not call `loadApiKey()` from `@google/gemini-cli-core` to verify the keychain.\n\n\n## The Solution / Discussion\n### Response 1\nCannot replicate on main, so it appears to be fixed.\n\n", "timestamp": null, "embedding": [0.29969021677970886, 1.4440466165542603, -3.145510196685791, -0.8245514631271362, 1.590919852256775, -0.6961094737052917, 0.176291823387146, 0.009289881214499474, -0.06968658417463303, -1.1030035018920898, -0.7980669140815735, 1.6883823871